article.headline: Haynes leads Hilltoppers with 29 points
article.linkText: Western Kentucky defeats Kent St. in OT
article.story:
BOWLING GREEN, Ky. (AP) -- Antonio Haynes scored 29 points and
had three steals, leading Western Kentucky to an 88-80 overtime
victory over mistake-plagued Kent State in an NIT opening-round
game Wednesday night.

	   Anthony Winchester scored 20 points and Courtney Lee added 17
for the Hilltoppers (22-8), who generated 33 points off Kent
State's season-high 28 turnovers.

	   Jay Youngblood scored a career-high 29 points on 13-of-18
shooting for the Golden Flashes (20-13), who were flustered
throughout by the Hilltoppers' trapping zone defense.

	   Western Kentucky advances to play Wichita State, an 85-69 winner
over Houston.

	   The teams ended regulation tied at 61, and Haynes put the
Hilltoppers ahead for good when he was fouled while swishing a
3-pointer from the corner. He made the ensuing free throw, giving
Western Kentucky a 67-64 lead.

	   Two minutes later, Kent State's 28th turnover resulted in a
3-pointer by Winchester and Western Kentucky had its largest lead,
76-66.

	   The Golden Flashes cut the lead to four, but the Hilltoppers
shot 6-for-6 from the free-throw line in the final 37.8 seconds to
put the game away.

	   Kent State was sloppy from the start, committing seven turnovers
in the opening 13 minutes. But Youngblood hit his first six shots,
all of them layups, to help the Golden Flashes to a 19-13 lead.

	   The Hilltoppers missed 12 of their first 18 shots, then mounted
a 12-3 run, helped by three Kent State miscues. Haynes' steal and
breakaway layup finished the spurt, giving the Toppers a 25-22 lead
with 4:25 left in the first half.

	   The Golden Flashes ended the half with a 9-2 burst, capped by
Jason Edwin's 3-pointer from the corner with 35 seconds left.

	   But Kent State continued to struggle with the Toppers' defense
after the break, passing its previous season-high turnover total
(19) seven minutes into the second half.

	   Lee dunked an alley-oop pass from Haynes with 8:22 remaining to
give Western Kentucky a 50-42 lead, its biggest to that point.

	   The Golden Flashes held the Hilltoppers scoreless for two
minutes and forged a 52-all tie by the 5-minute mark.

	   The Hilltoppers led 61-59 and had the ball as the clock went
under 30 seconds, but Edwin tipped a bad pass to Kevin Warzynski
near midcourt. Edwin immediately got the ball back from Warzynski
and drove for the tying dunk.

	   Ty Rogers shot an airball from the corner on Western's last
possession of regulation.
